.TH "NAVIGATOR.PLATFORM" "3JS" "August 25, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Navigator.platform \- Navigator: platform property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]platform\f[B]\f[R] property read\-only property of the
\f[CR]Navigator\f[R] interface returns a string identifying the platform
on which the user\(cqs browser is running.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] In general, you should whenever possible avoid writing
code that uses methods or properties like this one to try to find out
information about the user\(cqs environment, and instead write code that
does feature detection.
.RE
.SH VALUE
A string identifying the platform on which the user\(cqs browser is
running; for example: \f[CR]\(dqMacIntel\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqWin32\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqLinux x86_64\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqLinux armv81\(dq\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
\f[CR]navigator.platform\f[R] should almost always be avoided in favor
of feature detection.
But there is one case where, among the options you could use,
\f[CR]navigator.platform\f[R] may be the least\-bad option: When you
need to show users advice about whether the modifier key for keyboard
shortcuts is the \f[CR]⌘\f[R] command key (found on Apple systems)
rather than the \f[CR]⌃\f[R] control key (on non\-Apple systems):
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] modifierKeyPrefix =
  navigator.platform.startsWith(\(dqMac\(dq) || navigator.platform === \(dqiPhone\(dq
    ? \(dq⌘\(dq \f[I]// command key\f[R]
    : \(dq\(ha\(dq; \f[I]// control key\f[R]
.EE
.PP
That is, check if \f[CR]navigator.platform\f[R] starts with
\f[CR]\(dqMac\(dq\f[R] or else is an exact match for
\f[CR]\(dqiPhone\(dq\f[R], and then based on whether either of those is
true, choose the modifier key your web application\(cqs UI will advise
users to press in keyboard shortcuts.
.SH USAGE NOTES
On Windows, modern browsers return \f[CR]\(dqWin32\(dq\f[R] even if
running on a 64\-bit version of Windows.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
